4jf.title: The alternating group on five elements is simple
4jf.clickbait: The smallest (nontrivial) simple group is the alternating group on five elements.
4jf.text:
[todo: add the requisites for Cauchy etc]

The [-4hf] $A_5$ on five elements is [4jc simple].

# Proof

Suppose $H$ is a normal subgroup of $A_5$, which is not the trivial subgroup $\{ e \}$.
If $H$ has [3gg order] divisible by $3$, then by [cauchy_theorem_on_subgroup_existence Cauchy's theorem] there is a $3$-[49f cycle] in $H$ (because the $3$-cycles are the only elements with order $3$ in $A_5$).
Because $H$ [4jw is a union of conjugacy classes], $H$ would therefore contain *every* $3$-cycle; but then [4hs it would be the entire alternating group].

If instead $H$ has order divisible by $2$, then there is a double transposition such as $(12)(34)$ in $H$, since these are the only elements of order $2$ in $A_5$.
But then $H$ contains the entire conjugacy class so it contains every double transposition; in particular, it contains $(12)(34)$ and $(15)(34)$, so it contains $(15)(34)(12)(34) = (125)$.
Hence as before $H$ contains every $3$-cycle so is the entire alternating group.

So $H$ must have order exactly $5$, by [4jn Lagrange's theorem]; so it contains an element of order $5$ since [4jh prime order groups are cyclic].

The only such elements of $A_n$ are $5$-cycles; but the conjugacy class of a $5$-cycle is of size $12$, which is too big to fit in $H$ which has size $5$.
